$\displaystyle \frac{1}{6}$ of a ton of hay costs $\displaystyle \frac{4}{5}$ of an eagle. How many eagles does $\displaystyle \frac{2}{3}$ of a ton of hay cost?

}

\textbf{Answer:} Scaling $\displaystyle \frac{1}{6}$ of a ton of hay by $4$ gives $\displaystyle \frac{2}{3}$ of a ton of hay.  Scaling the corresponding costs, we see that $\displaystyle \frac{4}{5}\cdot 4 = \boxed{\frac{16}{5}}$ eagles.
